<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-733-574  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 733 574.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  August 1990 v15 n8 p217(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Natural selection: you don't have to be a programmer to query yourdatabase. (natural-language query systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Obermeier, Klaus K.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Natural-language query systems (NLQSs) ease retrieval ofinformation from data base management systems (DBMSs) by acceptingqueries in 'potentially ambiguous' natural English andtransforming that input into the unambiguous form that the DBMSnormally accepts.andP;  The central goal of NLQSs is to enable use ofDBMSs without having to learn another computer language, butcurrent NLQS technology can not process more than one or twonatural language strings at a time.andP;  Consequently, users shouldnot have high expectations of NLQSs but should be familiar withthe data base contents.andP;  NLQSs technology ranges from simplekeyword matching to ones that perform complex inferenceprocessing.andP;  The systems can be classified by host hardware,structure (pattern-based, knowledge-based or syntactic), andwhether the NLQS creates an outer later of data representation oris just a host to the DBMS.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Natural Language InterfacesQuery ProcessingFunctionsMethodsUtilizationData base management systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Basic NLQS function. (chart)Mapping considerations: many-to-one mapping, one-to-many mapping.andO;(chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>